10.body: Point Mass Outside a Spherical Shell - the gravitational force experienced by the point mass is the same as if all the shell's mass were concentrated at its centre Proof: Point Mass Outside a Spherical Shell Let the point mass be m and let it be located a distance r from the centre of the shell. Consider a ring on the surface of the shell. This ring is composed of components mi​ which are all a distance s from the point mass. The potential energy, dU, of the interaction between m and the entire ring is given by the potential energies between the point mass and every component of the ring: dU=i=0∑n​(−sGmmi​​)=−sGm​dM where the mass of the entire ring is dM=i=0∑n​mi​ The radius of the shell is R and so the radius of the ring is Rsinϕ. Its width is Rdθ and its area is approximately its width times its circumference: dA=2πR2sinϕdϕ The ration of the ring's mass to the shell's total mass is the same as the ring's are to the shell's are because of the uniformity of the distribution. MdM​=AdA​=4πR22πR2sinϕdϕ​=21​sinϕdϕ It is now possible to substitute in the expression for the ring's potential energy: dU=−2sGMmsinϕ​dϕ The total potential energy is the integral as s varies from r−R to r+R. The Pythagorean theorem can be used to find a relationship between s and ϕ: s2=(r−Rcosϕ)2+(Rsinϕ)2=r2−2rRcosϕ+R2 Take the differential of both sides: 2sds=2rRsinϕdϕ⟹dsindϕ=rRs​ds Substitute in the expression for dU and integrate: dU=−2sGMm​rRs​ds=−2rRGMm​ds U=−2rRGMm​∫r−Rr+R​ds=−rGMm​ This is identical to the potential energy formula if all the shell's mass were concentrated at its centre point. The force of gravity is conservative ( Fg​=−drdU​ ) which makes this equivalent hold for both the potential energy and the force. This holds for the more general case of a sphere because the latter can be thought of as a collection of concentric spherical shells and superposition of forces applies. The same holds true for two spherical mass distributions. Point Mass Inside a Spherical Shell - the gravitational force experienced by the point mass is zero and its potential energy is constant Proof: Point Mass Inside a Spherical Shell Much of the previous analysis applies here, but the limits of integration have to be changed in the end: U=−2rRGMm​∫R−rR+r​ds=−RGMm​ The potential energy therefore does not depend on the distance between the point mass and the centre of the sphere. a) point mass inside a solid, uniform-density sphere Fg​=R3GMm​r Point Mass Inside a Solid Sphere Derivation: The gravitational force experienced by the point mass ( m ) is only the gravitational force caused by the spherical mass distribution with a radius equal to the distance between m and the centre of the sphere. This is true because the outer part of the solid sphere can be thought of as a collection of concentric shells and since the point mass is inside them, they do exert a net gravitational force on it equal to zero. Let the inner spherical segment have a radius r and mass Minner​. The ratio of its mass to the mass of the entire sphere M is equal to the ratio of their volumes due to the uniform density. MMinner​​=34​πR334​πr3​⟹Minner​=R3r3​=MR3r3​ The gravitational force is Fg​=r2GMinner​m​=r2Gm​(MR3r3​)=R3GMm​r Therefore, inside a solid, uniform-density sphere, the gravitational force experienced by a point mass is proportional to 1/r instead of 1/r2

11.body: True Weight ( w0​ )- the total gravitational force exerted on an object by all other objects in the universe a) free-fall acceleration ( g ) - the same for all objects Proof: Suppose that a planet has mass M and a smaller mass m is in free fall. The gravitational forces caused by the rest of the objects in the universe are negligible, since they are too far away. The only force acting on m1​ (ignoring air resistance) is then the gravitational force: Fg​=ma Gr2Mm​=ma⟹a=r2GM​ Therefore, the object's acceleration is independent of its mass and we call this acceleration g. b) distance variance - weight is inversely proportional to the distance Apparent Weight ( w )- the weight measured by an observer, which is different from the true weight because the Earth is rotating w=w0​−marad​
11.title: Newtonian Mechanics

13.body: Displacement, time and average velocity Displacement, time and average velocity a) displacement - a vector pointing from the start point to the end point its x-component, denoted Δx is the change in the value of x b) average velocity - a vector whose x-component is the change in x divided by the time interval vav​=ΔtΔx​=t2​−t1​x2​−x1​​ movement in the positive x-direction ⟹vav​>0 movement in the negative x-direction ⟹vav​<0 Instantaneous Velocity (or just velocity) - the average velocity as the displacement and the time interval become arbitrarily small v=Δt→0lim​ΔtΔx​=dtdx​ a) sign - the same rules apply as those for the sign of average velocity b) speed - the magnitude of velocity which is always non-negative Acceleration a) average acceleration - a vector whose x-component is the change in velocity divided by the time interval aav​=ΔtΔv​=t2​−t1​v2​−v1​​ b) instantaneous acceleration - the average acceleration as the time interval gets arbitrarily small ax​=Δt→0lim​ΔtΔv​=dtdv​ Motion with Constant Acceleration a) velocity v=∫adt=v0​+at b) position x=∫vdt=21​at2+v0​t+x0​ c) relationships which do not depend on time or acceleration - these can be derived by substitutimg into the above two equations v2=v02​+2a(x−x0​) x−x0​=21​(v0​+v)t Free Fall - motion with (nearly) constant acceleration under the influence of gravity a) acceleration due to gravity - its magnitude is denoted by g g=9.8 m/s²

14.body: Position - a vector r=x^+y^​+zk^ a) displacement - overall change in the position Δr=r2​−r1​=(x2​−x1​)^+(y2​−y1​)^​+(z2​−z1​)k^ Velocity a) average velocity - the displacement over the time period vav​=ΔtΔr​=t2​−t1​r2​−r1​​ b) instantaneous velocity - the velocity as the time period gets arbitrarily small v=Δt→0lim​ΔtΔr​=dtdr​ always tangent to the path component-wise: vx​=dtdx​,vy​=dtdy​,vz​=dtdz​ speed - the magnitude of instantaneous velocity v=∣v∣=vx2​+vy2​+vz2​​ direction for 2D motion Motion direction in 2d tanα=vx​vy​​ Acceleration a) average acceleration - the overall change in velocity over the time period aav​=ΔtΔv​=t2​−t1​v2​−v1​​ b) instantaneous acceleration - the average acceleration as the time period gets arbitrarily small a=Δt→0lim​ΔtΔv​=dtdv​ component-wise ax​=dtdvx​​,ay​=dtdvy​​,az​=dtdvy​​ ax​=dt2d2x​,ay​=dt2d2y​,az​=dt2d2z​ c) parallel and perpendicular components - 2D acceleration can be written as components relating to velocity Parallel and Perpendicular components of acceleration the parallel component a∥​ - shows changes in speed : a∥​=acos∠(a,v) the perpendicular component a⊥​ - shows changes in direction : a⊥​=asin∠(a,v) Speed and Direction from Acceleration

15.body: Uniform Circular Motion - motion in a circle with a constant speed Circular Motion Acceleration a) average acceleration magnitude aav​=Δt∣Δv∣​=Rv​ΔtΔs​,(v=∣v1​∣=∣v2​∣) Derivation: Since OP1​⊥v1​ and OP2​⊥v2​, it follows that ∠P1​OP2​=∠(v1​,O,v2​)=Δϕ (move the velocity vectors so that they begin at O). Therefore, △P1​OP2​∼△(v1​​,O,v2​​)⟹Rv​=Δs∣Δv∣​ ∣Δv∣=Rv​Δs⟹aav​=Δt∣Δv∣​=Rv​ΔtΔs​ b) radial acceleration - the instantaneous acceleration, which is the limit as Δt→0 arad​=Rv2​ Derivation: Δt→0lim​ΔtΔs​=dtds​=v Properties: always perpendicular to the velocity and pointing towards the centre c) period ( T,[s] ) - the time for one revolution around the circle. In this time, a distance of 2πR is travelled and since the speed is constant: v=T2πR​⟹arad​=T24π2R​ Non-uniform Circular Motion - motion around a circular path with non-constant velocity Non-uniform Circular Motion Acceleration a) acceleration - also non-constant and with two components radial acceleration - the component perpendicular to the velocity (the same as with uniform circular motion) arad​≡a⊥​=Rv2​ tangential acceleration - the component parallel to the velocity (the change in speed) atan​≡a∥​=dtd∣v∣​=dtdv​

16.body: Rigid Body - an idealised model of an object with perfectly definite shape and size which do not change Rotational Motion - always occurs around a certain axis and in a particular plane a) angular position ( θ,[rad] ) - the angle the object makes in the plane with respect to a fixed axis in it angular displacement ( Δθ ) - the difference in the angle at two different times Angular Displacement b) angular velocity - the same for all points of a rigid body Angular Velocity ( ω,[rad/s] ) - a pseudovector representation of rotational motion a) magnitude - the angular speed ( ω≥0 ) b) direction - always perpendicular to the direction of rotation Angular Velocity c) components - it is useful to examine angular velocity in a coordinate system relative to the object's orientation in space so that we only have to deal with one of angular velocity's components: the axis of rotation conventionally being the z-axis and the plane of rotation being the xy-plane ωz​=dtdθ​ d) units 1 rev/s=2π rad/s 1 rpm=1 rev/min=602π​ rad/s Angular Acceleration ( α,[rad/s²] ) - the change in angular velocity (both the axis of rotation as well as speed) α=dtdω​ a) fixed axis of rotation - the acceleration lies on the axis of rotation αz​=dtdωz​​=dt2d2θ​ b) equations of rotation with constant acceleration - identical to the equations for 1D motion with constant linear acceleration Relations to Linear Kinematics - every point of the rigid body is undergoing circular motion at a constant distance r from the axis of rotation a) speed v=rω Linear and Angular Speed Derivation: s=rθ ​dtds​​=r​dtdθ​​ b) acceleration atan​=dtdv​=rdtdω​=rα arad​=rv2​=ω2r
16.title: Newtonian Mechanics

18.body: Work ( W,[J] ) - the energy transferred to or from an object via the application of a constant force along a displacement W=F⋅s a) sign Work Sign positive - the force is acting in the general direction of the displacement zero - the force is acting perpendicular to the displacement negative - the force is acting in the opposite of the general direction of the displacement b) total work - the sum of the work done by all the different forces or the work done by the net force Wtotal​=Fnet​⋅s≡i=1∑n​Wi​=i=1∑n​Fi​⋅s relation to speed - the total work needed to change the speed of an object from v1​ to v2​ Wtotal​=21​m(v22​−v12​) Derivation: The force is constant and so is the acceleration. Therefore, Wtotal​=F⋅s=m(a⋅s) v2x2​=v1x2​+2ax​sx​⟹ax​=2sx​v2x2​−v1x2​​ v2y2​=v1y2​+2ay​sy​⟹ay​=2sy​v2y2​−v1y2​​ v2z2​=v1z2​+2az​sz​⟹az​=2sz​v2z2​−v1z2​​ Wtotal​=m(a⋅s)=m(ax​sx​+ay​sy​+az​az​)=21​m(v2x2​−v1x2​+v2y2​−v1y2​+v2z2​−v1z2​) Wtotal​=21​m[v2x2​+v2y2​+v2z2​−(v1x2​+v1y2​+v1z2​)]=21​m(∣v2​∣2−∣v1​∣2)=21​m(v22​−v12​)≡21​mv22​−21​mv12​ c) units Joule 1 J=1 N⋅1 m kilowatt-hour - the work done in 1 hour when the power is one kilowatt 1 kWh=3.6×106 J Work with Varying Forces - the force may vary but for an infinitesimally small displacement, it is practically constant Work with Varying Forces W=∫P1​P2​​F⋅dl=∫P1​P2​​Fcosϕdl=∫P1​P2​​F∥​dl Power ( P,W ) - the rate at which work is done with respect to time a) average power - the work done for a given time interval Pav​=ΔtΔW​ relation to force and velocity Pav​=ΔtF⋅Δs​=F∥​ΔtΔs​=F∥​vav​ b) instantaneous power - the limit of the average powrt as the time interval approaches 0 P=Δt→0lim​ΔtΔW​=dtdW​ relation to velocity P=F⋅v c) units Watt 1 W=1 s1 J​ horsepower 1 hp=746 W

19.body: Kinetic Energy - the work required to bring an object from rest to a certain speed K=21​mv2 a) work-energy theorem - the total work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy ΔK=K2​−K1​=21​mv22​−21​mv12​=Wtotal​
19.title: Newtonian Mechanics

20.body: Potential Energy ( U,[J] ) - the amount of work that a system is capable of doing by means of a certain interaction a) conservative forces - a force which offers a two-way conversion between kinetic and potential energy can be expressed as the difference between the initial and final values of a potential-energy function reversible independent of the path of an object and only depending on the start and end point the total work is zero when the starting and ending point are the same W=−ΔU b) conservative force from potential energy F=−(∂x∂U​^+∂y∂U​^​+∂z∂U​k^)=−∇U Derivation: Since W=−ΔU, Fx​=−ΔxΔU​,Fy​=−ΔyΔU​,Fz​=−ΔzΔU​ Taking the limit, we get: Fx​=−dxdU​,Fy​=−dydU​,Fz​=−dzdU​ And the force vector therefore looks like: F=Fx​^+Fy​^​+Fz​k^=−dxdU​^−dydU​^​−dzdU​k^=−(∂x∂U​^+∂y∂U​^​+∂z∂U​k^) Gravitational Potential Energy - the work that an object can do when under the influence of gravity Gravitational Potential Energy a) definition - the work that an object will do when it falls from a certain height to the ground Ugrav​=mgy b) change in gravitational potential energy ΔUgrav​=−Wgrav​ Derivation: Wgrav​=w(y1​−y2​)=mgy1​−mgy2​=Ugrav, 1​−Ugrav, 2​=−(Ugrav, 2​−Ugrav, 1​)=−ΔUgrav​ Notice that this holds true even along a curved path: Wgrav​=w⋅Δs=−mg^​⋅(Δx^+Δy^​)=−mgΔy Curved Path Gravitational Potential Energy c) gravitational potential energy for an extended body - the same as if all the mass was concentrated at the centre of mass Ugrav​=Mgycm​ Derivation: The potential energy for the system is the sum of the potential energies of its components. If the difference in the gravitational force is negligible, then Ugrav​=i=1∑n​mi​gyi​=gi=1∑n​mi​yi​=gMycm​ Elastic Potential Energy - the work that a spring can do when released from a certain displacement Uel​=21​kx2 Derivation: The force a string stretched by an amount of x exerts on an object depends on the displacement x as per Hooke's law. This force is equal to kx and the work it does for an infinitesimally small displacement dx is given by the following integral: ∫0x​kxdx=k∫0x​xdx=21​kx2 Notice that the spring force acts along the displacement once the spring is released and so its work must be positive. Internal Energy ( Uint​,[J] ) - the energy associated with nonconservative forces acting on a system a) change in internal energy - the negative of the work done on the system by nonconservative forces ΔUint​=−Wother​

22.body: Moment of Inertia ( I,[kg⋅m²] ) - the sum of the products between the mass and distance from the rotational axis of every component of the system I=i=1∑n​mi​ri2​ a) properties the higher the moment of inertia, the more difficult it is to make a system rotate every body has infinitely many moments of inertia, since they are different for every access of rotation Moment of Inertia b) parallel axis theorem - a simple relationship between the moment of inertia about an axis which is parallel to an axis going through the centre of mass IP​=Icm​+Md2 Parallel Axis Theorem Derivation: Parallel Axis Theorem Proof Consider two axes parallel to the z-axis - one going through the centre of mass and another going through a point P(a,b). The distance between the two axes is given by d2=a2+b2. Take a mass element mi​ with coordinates (xi​,yi​,zi​). The moment of inertia around the centre-of-mass axis is then given by: Icm​=i=1∑n​mi​(xi2​+yi2​) The moment of inertia around the axis which goes through P is given by: IP​=i=1∑n​mi​[(xi​−a)2+(yi​−b)] Expanding and rearranging... IP​=i=1∑n​mi​(xi2​+yi2​)−2ai=1∑n​mi​xi​−2bi=1∑n​mi​yi​+(a2+b2)i=1∑n​mi​ The first term is just Icm​. From the definition of the centre of mass, the second and third terms are equal to −2aMxcm​ and −2bMycm​, respectively, but these are both 0 on account that the centre of mass is at the origin of our chosen coordinate system. The last term is just the distance between the centre of mass times the total mass, which completes the proof. c) moment of inertia for rigid bodies with continuous mass distributions I=∫r2dm=∫r2ρdV Kinetic Energy a) rotation only K=21​Iω2 Derivation: The angular velocity for every component of the system is the same (otherwise the body wouldn't be rigid) and so the speed of the i-th component is given by vi​=ri​ω Therefore, its kinetic energy is Ki​=21​mi​ri2​ω2 The total kinetic energy of the system is then K=21​(i=1∑n​mi​ri2​)ω2 And we define the moment of inertia to be I=i=1∑n​mi​ri2​ b) combined translation and rotation K=21​mvcm2​+21​Icm​ω2 Derivation: Kinetic Energy from Translation and Rotation We are going to use the fact that the motion of any rigid body can be represented as a translation of the centre of mass and a rotation about it. The velocity of the i-th component relative to an inertial frame of reference, vi​ is given by the velocity of the centre of mass vcm​ plus the component's velocity relative to the centre of mass, vi′​, which is purely rotational: vi​=vcm​+vi′​ The kinetic energy of this component in the inertial frame of reference is given by: Ki​=21​mi​vi2​ Now, vi2​ is equal to vi​⋅vi​ and so Ki​=21​mi​(vi​⋅vi​) Ki​=21​mi​(vcm​+vi′​)⋅(vcm​+vi′​)=21​mi​(vcm​⋅vcm​+2vcm​⋅vi′​+vi′​⋅vi′​)=21​mi​(vcm2​+2vcm​⋅vi′​+vi′2​) The total kinetic energy is K=i=1∑n​Ki​=21​(i=1∑n​mi​)vcm2​+vcm​⋅(i=1∑n​mi​vi′​)+i=1∑n​mi​vi′2​ The first term is just 21​Mvcm2​. The second term is zero because ∑mi​vi​​′ is M times the velocity of the centre of mass relative to the centre of mass which is 0. The third term is just 21​Icm​ω2. Work and Power a) work W=∫θ1​θ2​​τdθ Derivation: Suppose that a force acts on the rim of a pivoted disk. Only the tangential component of this force acts to change the rotation of the disk. For an infinitesimally small angle of rotation dθ, a point on the rim moves ds=Rdθ. The infinitesimally small amount of work done by the force is then dW=Ftan​ds=Ftan​Rdθ=τdθ The total work done for an angular displacement Δθ=θ2​−θ1​ is then given by the integral W=∫θ1​θ2​​τdθ Properties: the work done by the net torque equals the total change in rotational kinetic energy b) power P=τω Derivation: dW=τdθ dtdW​=τdtdθ​
22.title: Newtonian Mechanics

24.body: Force - a vector which describes an interaction between two objects a) magnitude ( F,[N = kg ⋅m/s²] ) - measured in Newtons b) superposition - any number of forces applied to the same point on an object have the same effect as a single force which is the vector sum of the forces called the net force Fnet​=i=1∑n​Fi​ Fnet​=Fx2​+Fy2​+Fz2​​ Weight - the gravitational force which Earth exerts on an object w=mg​ Normal Force ( n,Fn​ ) - a reaction force which appears whenever an object is pressed against a surface. a) direction always perpendicular to the surface always pointing away from the surface b) magnitude - the magnitude of the component of the pressing force which acts directly towards the surface normal force caused by weight n=wcosθ Normal Force on Incline Derivation: We choose our coordinate system to be the along the incline and the normal force. The y-component of the weight of the block is thus the one acting towards the surface and it is wy​=−wcosθ. The normal force in this coordinate system has only a y-component but it is in the opposite direction of that of the weight and so ny​=−wy​=−(−wcosθ)=wcosθ⟹n=wcosθ Notice that this holds true even when there is no incline and so θ=0. The cosine of zero is one and so the normal force would be equal in magnitude to the entire weight of the block, which is what you would expect.

25.body: First Law of Motion - an object acted on by no net external force has a constant velocity and no acceleration a) equilibrium - when an object is either at rest or moving with constant velocity Fnet​=0 b) intertial frame of reference - a frame of reference which is not undergoing any acceleration the first law is only valid in such a frame of reference a frame of reference B is inertial if it moves with a constant velocity relative to an inertial frame of reference A Second Law of Motion - if a net external force acts on an object, the object accelerates. This law is only valid for intertial frames of reference. Newton's Second Law Fnet​=ma a) direction of acceleration - the same as the direction of the force b) magnitude of acceleration - directly proportional to the magnitude of the force inertial mass ( m,[kg] ) - the ability to resist acceleration m=a∣Fnet​∣​⇔∣Fnet​∣=ma⇔a=m∣Fnet​∣​ Third Law of Motion - if object A exerts a force on object B, then object B exerts a force on object A which has the same magnitude but is opposite in direction Newton's Third Law FA on B​=−FB on A​ These forces act on different objects and so don't cancel each other out.
25.breadcrumbs: Newtonian Mechanics » Dynamics » 2. Newton's Laws of Motion
25.title: Newtonian Mechanics

26.body: Mechanism - when two surfaces come into contact, chemical bonds between them start breaking and forming which cause forces between them. When an external force is applied, friction forces occur between the two surfaces which try to counteract its effects. Friction Static Friction Force ( f​s​ ) - before an object can start sliding across a service, a force with a certain magnitude needs to be exerted on it. If a force ( F ) less than the force required is applied, the object does not move because the surface is exerting an opposite force called the static friction force . The latter, however, can only grow so large and when it is overcome, the object starts moving. a) magnitude fs​=F,F≤(fs​)max​ b) direction - opposite to the applied force's component which is perpendicular to the normal force c) maximum static friction force - proportional to the normal force (fs​)max​=μs​n μs​∈(0;1) - coefficient of static friction once this magnitude is reached, static friction has no further effect and kinetic friction kicks in Kinetic Friction Force ( f​k​ ) - the force which acts on an object as it slides on a surface a) magnitude - approximately proportional to the magnitude of the normal force fk​=μk​n μk​∈(0;1) - coefficient of kinetic friction b) direction - always perpendicular to the normal force Friction Force ( f​ ) - either the static friction force or the kinetic friction force at any time Fluid Resistance - the force that a fluid exerts on an object passing through it Fluid Resistance Motion Comparison a) direction - always opposite the object's velocity relative to the fluid b) magnitude for small speeds f=kv k,[N⋅s/m=kg/s] - a proportionality constant which depends on the shape and size of the object for high speeds - also called drag f=Dv2 D,[N⋅s²/m²=kg/m] - drag coefficient c) terminal velocity - motion in a fluid does not have constant acceleration, since the motion fluid resistance depends on speed. Therefore, if an external force is actively accelerating an object through a fluid, its speed will grow, but so will the fluid resistance until it fully cancels out the external force. At this point, the velocity of the object becomes constant - it is at its terminal velocity. This is typically used in a context of falling. Fluid Resistance at low speeds Fy​=mg+(−kvy​)=may​ Terminal speed is reached when the acceleration is zero: mg−kvt​=0⟹vt​=kmg​ at high speeds Fy​=mg+(−Dvy2​)=may​ Terminal speed is reached when the acceleration is zero: mg−Dvt2​=0⟹vt​=Dmg​​ observations: objects with more mass have a higher terminal velocity and thus appear to fall faster through air
26.title: Newtonian Mechanics

27.body: Uniform Circular Motion - can result from any combination of forces so long as the net force always points to the centre and has a constant magnitude Fnet​=marad​=mRv2​
27.title: Newtonian Mechanics

28.body: Linear Momentum ( p​ ) - a quantity of motion which characterises how difficult it is if for a linearly moving mass to stop p​=mv a) intuition it is more difficult to stop a big mass (a train) moving at a certain speed rather than to stop a small mass (a bike) moving at the same speed it is more difficult to stop a mass moving at a high speed speed than to stop the same mass moving at a slow speed b) Newton's second law - as originally stated Fnet​=dtdp​​ c) conservation of momentum - if there is no net external force acting on a system, then the total momentum of its components is constant P=i=1∑n​p​i​=const dtdP​=0 Reasoning: When there is no net external force, the only forces acting in the system are internal ones between its components. According to Newton's third law, each of these forces begets a reaction force, thus changing the momenta of both interacting components. Since these forces are exactly equal in magnitude and opposite in direction, so are the changes in the momenta of the interacting components and their vector sum is 0. Impulse ( J ) - the amount of change in the momentum of an object that the net external force begets in the span of a given time period J=∫t1​t2​​Fnet​dt Intuition: J=∫t1​t2​​Fnet​dt=∫t1​t2​​dtdp​​dt=∫p1​p2​​dp​=p​2​−p​1​ Momentum vs Kinetic Energy a) momentum - describes the relation between the force and the time it needs to be applied for to bring a mass to a stop b) kinetic energy - describes the relation between the force and the distance over which it needs to be applied to bring a mass to a stop
28.breadcrumbs: Newtonian Mechanics » Dynamics » 5. Momentum and Impulse
28.title: Newtonian Mechanics

29.body: Centre of Mass - a mass-weighted average position of the components of a system rcm​=i=1∑n​mi​i=1∑n​mi​ri​​ а) solid homogeneous objects Centre of Mass if the object has a geometric centre, then the centre of mass is located there if an object has an axis of symmetry, the centre of mass lies on this axis the centre of mass need not be inside the object Relation to the total momentum of a system - the total momentum of a system is equal to the total mass times the velocity of the centre of mass P=Mvcm​ Derivation: vcm​=dtd​rcm​=i=1∑n​mi​i=1∑n​mi​dtdri​​​=i=1∑n​mi​i=1∑n​mi​vi​​=i=1∑n​mi​i=1∑n​p​i​​=M1​P Effect of external forces - when a system is under the influence of external forces, its centre of mass moves as if all the mass was concentrated there ∑Fext​=Macm​=dtdP​ Derivation: vcm​=Mi=1∑n​mi​vi​​ Mvcm​=i=1∑n​mi​vi​ Mdtd​vcm​=i=1∑n​mi​dtdvi​​ Macm​=i=1∑n​mi​ai​=i=1∑n​Fi​ Fi​ is the sum of the forces acting on the i-th component now of the system. Now, this sum includes forces which are both internal and external for the system, but Newton's third law tells us that the internal forces in the system will cancel out. Therefore, i=1∑n​Fi​ contains only the external forces. Additionally, Mdtd​vcm​=dtd​(Mvcm​)=dtdP​ Motion of Rigid Bodies - the motion of any rigid body can be represented as a translation of the centre of mass and a rotation about the centre of mass

3.body: Fluid - any substance which can flow and change the shape of the volume it occupies a) liquids - fluids with cohesion they change the shape of the volume they occupy but not the volume itself b) gases - fluids without cohesion capable of changing the volume itself Density ( ρ,[kg/m³] ) - the mass contained in a unit of volume ρ=Vm​ a) properties - things made from the same material have the same density b) specific gravity (relative density) - a pure number which is the ratio of the density of a material to the density of water at 4°C terrible misnomer Pressure ( p,[Pa] ) - the force perpendicular to a surface that a fluid exerts over the area of the surface p=dAdF⊥​​ Pressure a) units Pa = N/m² - pascal bar=105 Pa atm=101,325 Pa≈1.013×105 Pa - average atmospheric pressure at sea level b) Pascal's law - pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted undiminished to every portion of the fluid and the walls of its container c) depth and pressure - persuant to Pascal's law, the pressure in a fluid increases with depth because the upper layers of the fluid exert pressure on the lower ones p=p0​+ρgh p - pressure at depth h p0​ - pressure at the surface of the fluid Derivation: Depth and Pressure Imagine an element of a fluid which is at rest and which has a top and bottom surface area A, is located at an elevation y from the bottom of the container and has thickness dy. Its mass and weight are dm and dw, its density ρ its volume dV. Call the pressure at the bottom surface p and the pressure at the top surface p+dp, where dp is the change in pressure we are trying to find. The forces acting on the fluid element are its weight as well as the upward force the rest of the fluid exerts on the bottom of the element and the downward force it exerts on the top of the element (the sideways forces cancel out). Since the element is at equilibrium, the net force acting on it is zero: dw+dFup​+dFdown​=0 −dmgdV+pA−(p+dp)A=0 pA−(p+dp)A−ρgAdy=0 Dividing out the area and rearranging... dydp​=−ρg Therefore, the pressure decreases as y increases - moving upward means that you experience less pressure. Integrating both sides of the equation, we can obtain an expression for the total pressure difference between two points: ∫y1​y2​​dydp​dy=∫y1​y2​​−ρgdy p2​−p1​=−ρg(y2​−y1​) In order to represent the pressure difference based on a depth from the surface, we can take p to be the pressure at point 1 (the former p1​ and p0​ (0 for zero depth) to be the pressure at the surface (point 2, formerly p2​). Depth and Pressure Derivation The depth is h=y2​−y1​ and so p0​−p=−ρgh By rearranging, we obtain that p=p0​+ρgh d) relations to atmospheric pressure gauge pressure - the difference between the pressure inside a system and the atmospheric pressure outside it absolute pressure - the total pressure including atmospheric pressure
3.title: Newtonian Mechanics

30.body: Inelastic Collisions - the total kinetic energy after the collision is less than the total kinetic energy before it a) completely inelastic collisions - the two colliding objects stick together and continue their motion with the same velocity Completely Inelastic Collision mA​vA1​+mB​vB1​=(mA​+mB​)v2​ Elastic Collisions - the total kinetic energy of the system before and after the collision is preserved {mA​vA1​+mB​vB1​=mA​vA2​+mB​vB2​21​mA​vA12​+21​mB​vB12​=21​mA​vA22​+21​mB​vB22​​
30.title: Newtonian Mechanics

31.body: Torque ( τ,[N⋅m] ) - the tendency of a force to change an object's rotational motion about a certain point τ=Fl Torque a) lever arm ( l ) - the distance between the axis of rotation and the force's line of action b) sign positive - the torque induces counterclockwise rotation negative - the torque induces clockwise rotation c) vector representation τ=r×F Torque Vector d) rigid-body angular acceleration τ=Iα Derivation: Suppose that a force F acts on the i-th mass component of a rigid body, mi​, located a distance ri​ from the axis of rotation (the z-axis, for example). Only the force component which is tangent to the circle with radius ri​ (and is not parallel to the axis of rotation) induces torque on the mass component: τi​=Ftan​ri​=mi​atan,i​ri​=mi​ri2​α=Ii​α The body is rigid so the angular acceleration is the same for all of its components. Therefore, the net torque is given by τ=i=1∑n​τi​=αi=1∑n​Ii​=Iα centre of mass and angular acceleration - the rotation of a rigid body can be described by the following equation provided that the axis through the centre of mass is an axis of symmetry and that the axis does not change direction τnet​=Icm​α Angular Momentum L=r×p​ Angular Momentum a) magnitude and direction direction - perpendicular to the plane of rotation magnitude: L=mvrsinϕ=mvl b) rate of change - the torque of the net force dtdL​=τ Derivation: dtdL​=dtd​(r×p​)=dtdr​×p​+r×dtdp​​ The first term is zero because it contains the cross product of v with itself. The second term is equal to r×F, which is equal to the net torque. c) rigid bodies for an axis of rotation that is an axis of symmetry L=Iω Derivation: Angular Momentum of Rigid Body Every component of a rigid body is moving in a circle with the same angular velocity ω. Since the velocity at each point of the circle is tangent to its position vector, the magnitude of the angular momentum for the i-th component is given by Li​=mi​vi​ri​=mi​(ri​ω)ri​=mi​ri2​ω The total angular momentum for the slice is L=i=1∑n​Li​=ωi=1∑n​mi​ri2​=Iω Now, we need to add the angular momenta of the rest of the slices, but the position vectors for their elements have z-components and so their angular momenta will have components perpendicular to the z-axis. Fortunately, if the rotational axis is an axis of symmetry, these z-components will cancel out for the elements on opposite sides of the axis and so the angular momentum vector will lie on the same line as the angular velocity rotational axis is not an axis of symmetry - the angular momentum vector traces out a cone around the axis of rotation which means that there is a net external torque even though the angular velocity may be constant d) conservation of angular momentum - when the total net external torque is zero, the angular momentum of a system is constant e) precession - applying a torque to an object which already has angular momentum may result in peculiar motion Precession The wheel is spinning around an axis of symmetry and has an initial angular momentum due to this rotation equal to Li​. Its weight pulls down on it and so generates a torque τ perpendicular to L. This torque causes a change in the angular momentum which wants to follow the torque and so the wheel does not fall but its axis rather rotates. precession angular speed - the change in the direction of angular momentum Ω=Iωwr​
31.title: Newtonian Mechanics

32.body: Equilibrium - a state where an object does not undergo any change in motion a) static equilibrium - the object does not undergo any sort of acceleration and its velocity is zero b) dynamic equilibrium - the object undergoes uniform translational motion without any acceleration and rotation c) conditions for equilibrium there is no net external force there is no net external torque Equilibrium Conditions Centre of Gravity - the weight of an object does not act at a single point, but the torque generated by it can always be calculated by assuming that all the weight is concentrated at this point a) location when the acceleration due to gravity is uniform across an object - the centre of gravity is the same as the centre of mass for symmetrical objects - the centre of gravity lies on the axis of symmetry for objects in rotational equilibrium that are acted on only by gravity and are suspended at a single point - the centre of gravity is always at or directly above or below the point of suspension Centre of Gravity of Irregularly Shaped Object b) properties when the centre of gravity is outside the object's support, the object tips over the lower the centre of gravity, the more difficult it is to overturn an object Centre of Gravity Overturn
32.title: Newtonian Mechanics

33.body: Stress - a measure of the force per the area that it is applied over a) units pascal: Pa=N/m² Strain - a measure of the deformation caused by a certain amount of rest which is represented as the change in size divided by the original size) Hooke's Law - for a sufficiently small stress, the resulting strain is directly proportional to the stress with the proportionality constant being called the elastic modulus StrainStress​=Elastic modulus a) properties the elastic modulus depends on the material of the object but not its shape or size Young's Modulus ( Y,[Pa] ) - a material property a) for tension - when an object is stretched Young's Modulus Y=Tensile strainTensile stress​=AF⊥​​Δll0​​ b) for compression Young's Compressive Modulus Y=Compressive strainCompressive stress​=AF⊥​​Δll0​​ c) properties materials with large Y values are more difficult to stretch or compress most materials have the same Young moduli for tension and compression with stone and concrete being notable exceptions - the latter can withstand high compressive stress but fail under comparable tensile stress Bulk Modulus - a measure of how much the volume of an object changes due to a uniform pressure acting over its entire surface B=Bulk strainBulk stress​=−ΔV/V0​Δp​=−V0​ΔVΔp​ a) properties an increase in pressure causes a decrease in volume b) compressibility - the fractional decrease in volume per a unit change in pressure k=B1​=−V0​1​ΔpΔV​ Shear Modulus - forces are applied tangent to opposite sides of the object which causes one face to be displaced relative to its opposite face by a distance x S=Shear strainShear stress​=x/hF∥​​=AF∥​​xh​ Shear Stress and Strain a) shear stress Shear stress=AF∥​​ b) shear strain Shear strain=hx​ c) properties applies only to solid object the shear modulus for most materials is usually a third to a half of Young's modulus for tension Elasticity and Plasticity a) elastic deformations - deformations which are reversible and the object naturally returns to them after the stress is gone elastic hysteresis - a phenomenon where a material follows different curves for increasing and decreasing stress and does less work when returning to its original form than is needed to deform it Elastic Hysteresis b) plastic deformations - the object remains deformed even after the stress is gone c) stress-strain diagrams Stress-Strain Diagram proportional limit - the stress at which Hooke's law stops being obeyed yield point - the point at which elastic behaviour becomes plastic elastic limit - the stress at the yield point permanent set - the strain which remains after the stress in a plastic deformation has been removed

36.body: Definition Temperature scales a) Celcius - measured in degrees TC​=95​(TF​−32°) b) Fahrenheit - also measured in degrees but does not use the same increments and starting point as Celcius TF​=59​(TC​+32°) c) Kelvin - measured in kelvins and begins at absolute zero TK​=TC​+273.15
36.title: Thermodynamics

37.body: Definition - most materials expand when heated Linear expansion - for a solid rod with initial length L0​ and an initial temperature T0​, the change in length, ΔL is directly proportional to the change in temperature, ΔT, provided that ΔT is sufficiently small ( <100°C ). Additionally, ΔL is also directly proportional to L0​, since two rods made of the same material will expand at different rates when heated. ΔL=αL0​ΔT α,[K−1] - the coefficient of linear expansion which is specific to every material, depends on T0​ and ΔT, albeit to a limited degree Volume Expansion - similarly to linear expansion, there is a law of volume expansion ΔV=βV0​ΔT β,[K−1] - coefficient of volume expansion, which has the same subtleties as α a) relationship between the coefficients of linear and volume expansion β=3α Derivation: Consider a cube with side length L and a volume V=L3. dV=dLdV​dL=3L2dL dL=αL0​dT V0​=L03​⟹dV=3L02​αL0​dT=3αV0​dT This is consistent with dV=βV0​dT only if β=3α. Thermal Stress
37.title: Thermodynamics

38.body: Quantity of heat ( Q,[J] ) - the amount of energy which is transferred during heat flow; Q>0 means that heat flows in and Q<0 means that heat flows out a) calorie - the amount of heat requird to raise the temperature of 1 gram of water from 14.5°C to 15.5°C 1 cal=4.186 J a food-value calorie is actually a kilocalorie (kcal) and is 1000 times larger Specific Heat / Specific Heat Capacity ( c,[kg⋅KJ​] ) - the heat required to raise the temperature of 1 kg of a certain material by 1 K. It depends slightly on the initial temperature and the temperature interval but this is usually ignored. Q=cmΔT the total amount of heat required to raise the temperature of m kilograms of a given material by ΔT kelvins Molar Heat Capacity / Molar Specific Heat ( C ) - the product of the molar mass of a substance and its specific heat capacity C=Mc,[mol⋅KJ​] the toal amount of heat required to raise the temperature of n mols of a given substance by ΔT kelvins is then given by: Q=nCΔT a) Dulong-Petit law - the molar heat capacities for most elemental solids are the same: ≈25 J/mol⋅K Phase Transitions - for a given pressure, there is a temperature at which adding or substracting heat will not change the temperature of a system but will rather make it undergo a phase transition Phase Changes a) heat of fusion ( Lf​,[kgJ​]) - the heat required to change one kilogram of a solid to a liquid or vice versa the heat required to change m kilograms of a substance from solid to liquid or vice versa is given by Q=±mLf​ "+" for melting, "-" for freezing b) heat of vaporisation ( Lv​,[kgJ​] ) - the heat required to boil 1 kilogram of liquid or to condense 1 kilogram of vapour the heat required to boil/condense m kilograms of a substance is then given by: Q=±mLv​
38.title: Thermodynamics

39.body: Conduction - occurs between objects in contact with each other a) properties always from higher to lower temperatures b) heat current ( H[sJ​] ), the amount of heat, dQ which flows for a time dt through any homogeneous object with a cross section A perpendicular to the direction of heat flow and a path of heat-flow with a length L H=dtdQ​=kALTH​−TC​​ k,[m⋅KW​] - thermal conductivity which is specific to every material LTH​−TC​​ - the temperature difference per unit length, also called the magnitude of the temperature gradient proportional to the area of contact - because the heat has more area to enter into / exit from inversely proportional to the length of the conductor - because the longer the conductor is, the farther heat has to travel Heat Current through a Rod c) non-uniform temperature gradient - when temperature doesn't change in the same way along the length of the heat flow, the equation for the heat current takes on the infinitesimal form H=dtdQ​=−kAdxdT​ negative sign indicates that heat flows in the direction of decreasing temperature if temperature is increasing with increasing x, then dxdT​>0⟹H<0 and so heat flows in the negative x-direction (away from the higher temperature and into the lower one) d) thermal resistance ( R,[Wm2⋅K​] ) - defined for a slab of material with area A so that the heat current through it is H=RA(TH​−TC​)​ R=kL​ Convection - heat transfer by means of mass motion of a fluid from one region to another a) properties directly proportional to surface area fluid viscosity slows free convection near a stationary surface heat current due to free convection is approximately proportional to the 1.25 power of the temperature difference between the fluid and the surface b) types forced convection - a pump is moving the fluid free convection - the fluid moves due to density differences caused by thermal expansion Radiation - transfer of heat by electromagnetic waves given off every object a) Stefan-Boltzmann law H=AeσT4 A,[m2]: area of emitting surface e∈(0;1): emissivity of the surface - the ratio of the rate of radiation of a given surface to the rate of radiation of an ideal surface with the same area at the same temperature; often larger for dark surfaces σ=5.67037442×10−8 W / m²⋅K⁴: Stefan-Boltzmann constant T,[K] - absolute temperature b) absorption - the surrounds of a body also radiate and some of this radiation gets absorbed by the body. At thermal equilibrium, Tb​=Ts​ and so the rate of absorption must be given by H=AeσTs4​ net heat current of a body at temperature Tb​ and surrounds at temperature Ts​ Hnet​=Aeσ(Tb4​−Ts4​) Hnet​>0⟹ heat is flowing out of the body
39.title: Thermodynamics

4.body: The Buoyant Force a) Archimedes' principle - when an object is immersed in a fluid, the fluid exerts an upward force on the object equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the object Proof: Archimedes Principle Consider a fluid in equilibrium and, more specifically, an element in this fluid. The net force on it must be zero, therefore, the y-components of all the surface forces must neutralise the weight of the element - resulting in an upward force. Additionally, the net torque must also be zero and so the line of action of this force must pass through the element's centre of gravity. When the fluid element is replaced with an object of the same shape, the pressures remain the same and so does the buoyant force. Note that its line of action is still along the centre of gravity of the fluid element and not the object. b) properties depends only the fluid's density and the volume of the displaced fluid Floating - depends on the average densities of the object and the fluids ρobject​<ρfluid​⟹object floats and is only partially submerged ρobject​=ρfluid​⟹object is completely submerged but does not sink ρobject​>ρfluid​⟹object sinks
4.title: Newtonian Mechanics

5.body: Ideal Fluid - an incompressible fluid with no viscosity a) incompressible fluids - fluids with constant density liquids gases with a negligible pressure gradient over different regions Fluid Flow a) laminar flow - a steady fluid flow where adjacent layers of fluid slide past each other b) turbulent flow - an irregular and chaotic fluid flow which arises when a certain critical speed is reached depends on the viscosity - the more viscous the fluid, the more it is able to sustain laminar flow c) flow tube - the collection of imaginary flow lines which flow through the edge of a fluid element d) viscosity - internal friction in a fluid which opposes the motion of one portion of fluid relative to another temperature-dependent: proportional for gases and inversely proportional for liquids boundary layer - viscous fluids always form a layer on top of any solid they come in contact with which moves very slowly because fluids want to stick to solids pressure required to sustain a certain volume flow rate through a pipe when the fluid is viscous is proportional to R4L​ for the length and radius of the pipe, respectively Viscous Fluid Flow e) properties - mass remains constant when the fluid is flowing Flow Rates a) volume flow rate - the volume of the fluid which flows through a section of the fluid dtdV​=Av Derivation: The volume of fluid which flows through a small section of fluid is given by the section's cross-sectional area and the small distance the fluid travels for the small time interval. dV=Ads=Avdt⟹dtdV​=Av b) the continuity equation - the mass flowing through any section of the fluid is the same ρ1​A1​v1​=ρ2​A2​v2​ Derivation: The Continuity Equation dV1​=A1​v1​⟹ρ1​dm​=A1​v1​⟹dm=ρ1​A1​v1​ dV2​=A2​v2​⟹ρ2​dm​=A2​v2​⟹dm=ρ2​A2​v2​ c) incompressible fluids constant volume flow rate due to their constant density dtdV​=const⟹A1​v1​=A2​v2​ the fluid velocity in a section is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area Bernoullie's Equation - valid for laminar flow p+ρgy+21​ρv2=const Derivation: Bernoullie's Equation The fluid sections between a and b and c and d have cross-sectional areas A1​ and A2​, respectively, and the fluid through them moves with speeds v1​ and v2​. The fluid is ideal, therefore incompressible, and so dV=A1​ds1​=A2​ds2​. Pressure forces by the surrounding forces are at play and have magnitudes p1​A1​ and p2​A2​, respectively. The total work done by them is dW=p1​A1​ds1​−p2​A2​ds2​=(p1​−p2​)dV The work done by the second force is against the direction of displacement and thus has a negative sign. By the work-energy theorem, dW is equal to the net change in the kinetic and potential energy: dW=dK+dU The difference in kinetic energy is given by: dK=21​dm(v22​−v12​)=21​ρdV(v22​−v12​) The difference in potential energy is dU=dmg(y2​−y1​)=ρdVg(y2​−y1​) Combining the three equations... (p1​−p2​)dV=21​ρdV(v22​−v12​)+ρdVg(y2​−y1​) ⇓ p1​−p2​=21​ρv22​−21​ρv12​+ρgy2​−ρgy1​ Rearrange the terms to complete the proof: p1​+ρgy1​+21​ρv12​=p2​+ρgy2​+21​ρv22​

5.title: Newtonian Mechanics

7.body: Newton's Law of Gravitation - every object in the universe attracts every other object in the universe with a force that is directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them Fg​=Gr2m1​m2​​ a) direction of the gravitational force - along the line joining the two masses, forming an action-reaction pair b) magnitude - the same for both masses when you fall, you pull on the Earth just as much as it pulls on you, but you don't notice its movement because it is much more massive c) the gravitational constant - measured using a Cavendish torsion balance G=6.67408(31)×10−11[ m3kg−1s−2]≈6.67×10−11[ m3kg−1s−2] Cavendish Torsion Balance Spherical Mass Distributions a) gravity on the outside - the same as if all the sphere's mass were concentrated at the centre b) gravity on the inside zero for a spherical shell
7.title: Newtonian Mechanics

8.body: Gravitational Potential Energy - the potential energy stored in a system due to gravity U=−rGMm​ a) derivation Gravitational Potential Energy The work done by the gravitational force as the object moves from r1​ to r2​ is given by Wgrav​=−∫r1​r2​​Fg​dr The minus sign is there because gravity acts opposite the displacement. By substituting for the force of gravity we obtain Wgrav​=−GMm∫r1​r2​​r21​dr=r2​GMm​−r1​GMm​ This is the difference in the gravitational potential energies between the two distances, U1​−U2​ and so an appropriate formula for U would be U=−rGMm​ b) small distance approximation U=mgy Derivation: Wgrav​=GMmr1​r2​r1​−r2​​ When close to the Earth's surface r1​r2​ is approximately equal to the Earth's radius squared and so: Wgrav​=GMmR2r1​−r2​​ Similarly, the gravitational force varies very little for a small difference r1​−r2​ and is therefore given by GR2Mm​=mg. The potential energy then becomes U=mg(r1​−r2​) Negativity - gravitational potential energy is always negative a) essential property - gravitational potential energy always increases with distance this must be preserved in our definitions of gravitational potential energy b) reference point - gravitational potential energy is defined relative to a reference point which is taken to be at infinity and the gravitational potential energy there is defined to be zero when dealing with situations close to Earth's surface, it is easier to take the reference point to be at the Earth's surface and so gravitational potential energy is positive in order to preserve its essential property b) intuition - in order to separate two masses M and m by a distance r, a force needs to be applied and the work done by this force is positive. This work is equal to the difference in the two potential energies and the only way for it to be positive and for the gravitational potential energy to approach zero as the distance approaches infinity is for the gravitational potential energy to have been negative in the first place this preserves the property that gravitational potential increases (becomes less negative) as distance increases
8.title: Newtonian Mechanics

9.body: Escape Velocity - the minimum speed required for an object to escape the gravitational pull of a planet ve​=R2GM​​ a) derivation The energy of the object at the planet's surface is equal to the sum of its initial kinetic and gravitational energies: E1​=21​mv12​−RGMm​ In order for the object to escape the planet and not return to it, we want it to essentially stop only when it reaches infinity (i.e. never) and so the energy at that point would be given by E2​=21​mv22​−∞GMm​=0−0=0 By conservation of mechanical energy we have E1​=E2​⟹21​mv12​−RGMm​=0 By rearranging and dividing by m we obtain v1​=R2GM​​ Circular Orbits - the only force acting on the object is the gravitational pull it experiences and so it is undergoing uniform circular motion a) speed-radius relationship - the speed required for an orbit with a chosen radius is fixed and does not depend on the mass of the orbiting object, only on the mass of the object it is revolving around v=rGM​​ Derivation: The gravitational force experienced by the object is Gr2Mm​ and it is the only force acting on it so Gr2Mm​=ma. There is uniform circular motion so the acceleration is completely radial and a=rv2​. Equate the two formulas: Gr2Mm​=mrv2​ v=rGM​​ b) orbital period - the time it takes for one revolution around the orbit T=2πrGMr​​ Derivation: The period is just the length of the orbit divided by the object's speed. Therefore, the orbital period is also fixed for a given orbital radius. T=v2πr​=rGM​​2πr​=2πrGMr​​ Properties: larger orbital radii result in longer periods and slower orbital speeds c) total mechanical energy - given by the kinetic and potential energy for the orbit because the orbital speed and radius are fixed E=−2rGMm​=21​U Derivation: E=K+U=21​mv2−rGMm​=21​m(rGM​)−rGMm​ Kepler's Laws of Planetary Motion - corollaries of Newton's laws of motion and gravitation a) first law - each planet moves in an elliptical orbit with the star at one of its foci Kepler's First Law major and minor axes - the longest and smallest dimensions of the ellipse the semi-major and semi-minor axes - the half-lengths of the major and minor axes eccentricity ( e ) - a dimensionless number describing how squashed the ellipse is perihilion - the point closest to the star aphelion - the point farthest from the star SP+S′P=const b) second law - a line from the Star to a given planet sweeps out equal areas in equal times dtdA​=21​r2dtdθ​=const Kepler's Second Law Derivation: This law is a corollary of the conservation of angular momentum and essentially states that the sector velocity (dtdA​) is constant throughout the orbit. The angular momentum of the planet as it orbits around the star is L=mvl=mvrsinϕ The area swept out by the line SP is dA=21​r2dθ⟹dtdA​=21​r2dtdθ​=21​rv⊥​=21​rvsinϕ This is the magnitude of the cross product r×v=m1​L (recall the formula for angular momentum). Therefore, dtdA​=2m1​∣r×mv∣=2mL​ The right-hand side is constant because the only force acting on the planet is gravity and it causes no torque because it acts along the line SP. Kepler's Second Law (2) c) third law - the orbital period for a planet is proportional to the 3/2 power of its semi-major axis T2=GM4π2​a3 Centre of Mass - in reality, both the star and the planet orbit around their common centre of mass but this effect is negligible due their mass difference Orbital Centre of Mass
9.title: Newtonian Mechanics
